## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `ProductCatalogTests.cs`

### Summary

**10 tests. 0 verify behavior.** This is a textbook **coverage-touching** suite — every public method on `ProductCatalog` is called so coverage tools report ~95%, but almost nothing is actually asserted. Bugs in pricing, search, CSV parsing, and deletion would all pass these tests silently.

| Severity | Count |
|----------|-------|
| Critical | 7 |
| High | 1 |
| Medium | 1 |
| Low | 1 |

---

### Critical Findings

#### 1. Coverage Touching (systemic — all 10 tests)

The test class methodically calls every public method on `ProductCatalog` in declaration order with no meaningful assertions. This is the single root cause of your "95% coverage, still buggy" problem.

**6 tests with zero assertions** (lines 17–21, 33–36, 39–43, 64–66, 69–74, 85–88):

```csharp
// AddProduct_Works — no assertion at all
_catalog.AddProduct(product);

// UpdatePrice_Works — no assertion at all
_catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);

// RemoveProduct_Works — no assertion at all
_catalog.RemoveProduct("SKU-001");

// GetProductCount_Works — no assertion at all
var count = _catalog.GetProductCount();

// ApplyBulkDiscount_Works — no assertion at all
_catalog.ApplyBulkDiscount(0.10m);

// ImportFromCsv_Works — no assertion at all
_catalog.ImportFromCsv("SKU-001,Widget,9.99");
```

These tests prove only that the methods don't throw. They cannot catch:
- `UpdatePrice` saving the wrong price
- `RemoveProduct` leaving the product in the store
- `ApplyBulkDiscount` calculating the wrong amount
- `ImportFromCsv` parsing data incorrectly

**Fix — example for `UpdatePrice`:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void UpdatePrice_ExistingProduct_PriceIsUpdated()
{
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));

    _catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);

    var updated = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
    Assert.AreEqual(14.99m, updated!.Price);
}
```

**Fix — example for `ApplyBulkDiscount`:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void ApplyBulkDiscount_TenPercent_ReducesAllPrices()
{
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 10.00m));
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-002", "Gadget", 20.00m));

    _catalog.ApplyBulkDiscount(0.10m);

    Assert.AreEqual(9.00m, _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001")!.Price);
    Assert.AreEqual(18.00m, _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-002")!.Price);
}
```

#### 2. `Assert.IsNotNull` as Only Assertion (lines 28, 51, 59, 81)

Four tests assert only that the result is not null. `GetProduct`, `Search`, `GetAll`, and `ExportToCsv` all return non-null by contract (empty list/string), so `IsNotNull` can never fail. These are effectively assertion-free.

**`GetProduct_Works` (line 28)** — doesn't verify the returned product has the right SKU, name, or price:
